=E2=89=A1 a</span><sub><span>i</span></sub></p><p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"text=
-align: start;"><span>Thus, (x) is a solution to the system of congruences.=
</span></p><p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"text-align: start;"><b><strong>Uniquenes=
s</strong></b><span>:</span></p><p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"text-align: start;"=
><span>Suppose (x) and (x') are two solutions to the system of congruences.=
 We aim to show that (x =E2=89=A1 x' (mod N).</span></p><p dir=3D"ltr" styl=
e=3D"text-align: start;"><span>Let (m =3D x' - x). Since both (x) and (x') =
satisfy all the congruences, (m) must also satisfy them. Therefore, (m) is =
divisible by each of the moduli (n</span><sub><span>1</span></sub><span>, n=
</span><sub><span>2</span></sub><span>,...., n</span><sub><span>k</span></s=
ub><span>).</span></p><p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"text-align: start;"><span>By =
definition, (N =3D n</span><sub><span>1</span></sub><span> =C2=B7 n</span><=
sub><span>2</span></sub><span> =C2=B7....=C2=B7 n</span><sub><span>k</span>=
