(mod 105)</span></p><h2 id=3D"chinese-remainder-theorem-solution-for-not-co=
prime-moduli" style=3D"text-align:left"><span>Chinese Remainder Theorem Sol=
ution for Not Coprime Moduli</span></h2><p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"text-align:=
 start;"><span>Chinese Remainder Theorem helps in solving systems of equati=
ons where the remainders are congruent, even if the numbers that are divisi=
ble by are not relatively prime. But when the divisors are not relatively p=
rime, there might be more than one solution to the problem.</span></p><p di=
r=3D"ltr" style=3D"text-align: start;"><span>Suppose we have the following =
system of congruences:</span></p><p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"text-align: start;=
"><span>x =E2=89=A1 2 (mod 4)</span></p><p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"text-align:=
 start;"><span>x =E2=89=A1 6 (mod 6)</span></p><p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"text=
-align: start;"><span>Here, the moduli 4 and 6 are not coprime because thei=
r greatest common divisor (GCD) is 2</span></p><p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"text=
-align: start;"><span>To find the solution using the Chinese Remainder Theo=
rem, we proceed as follows:</span></p><p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"text-align: s=
tart;"><b><strong>1. </strong></b><span>Find the moduli product: Calculate =
(m =3D 4 =C3=97 6 =3D 24).</span></p><p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"text-align: st=
art;"><b><strong>2.</strong></b><span> Find the residues: Divide each modul=
us by the product of the other moduli to find the residue:</span></p><ul><l=
i value=3D"1"><span>4 =C3=97 k =E2=89=A1 1 (mod 6)</span></li><li value=3D"=
2"><span>6 =C3=97 k' =E2=89=A1 1 (mod 4)</span></li></ul><p dir=3D"ltr" sty=
le=3D"text-align: start;"><span>In this case, (k =3D 1) and (k' =3D 1) sati=
sfy the congruences, so the residues are both 1</span></p><p dir=3D"ltr" st=
yle=3D"text-align: start;"><b><strong>3.</strong></b><span> Calculate the s=
olution: The solution (x) is given by: x =3D a</span><sub><span>1</span></s=
ub><span> =C3=97 m</span><sub><span>2</span></sub><span> =C3=97 k + a</span=
><sub><span>2</span></sub><span> =C3=97 m</span><sub><span>1</span></sub><s=
pan> =C3=97 k' (mod m) </span></p><p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"text-align: start=
;"><span>Plugging in the values:</span></p><ul><li value=3D"1"><span>x =3D =
2 =C3=97 6 =C3=97 1 + 6 =C3=97 4 =C3=97 1...(mod 24)</span></li><li value=
=3D"2"><span>x =3D 12 + 24...(mod 24) </span></li><li value=3D"3"><span>x =
=3D 36...(mod 24) </span></li><li value=3D"4"><span>x =3D 12</span></li></u=
l><blockquote><p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"text-align: start;"><span>So, the sol=
ution for this system of congruences is x =E2=89=A1 12 (mod 24).</span></p>=
</blockquote><h3 id=3D"also-check" style=3D"text-align:left"><span>Also Che=
