aid" style=3D"text-align:left"><b><strong>Error correction</strong></b></h3=
><ul><li value=3D"1"><span>Reed-Solomon Codes recover data from corrupted s=
torage (e.g., CDs, QR codes) by encoding data as residues modulo coprime nu=
mbers. Even if some residues are lost/corrupted, original data can be recon=
structed. Ex.: RAID storage systems, satellite communications.</span></li><=
li value=3D"2"><span>Checksum Algorithms CRT-based checksums detect errors =
in distributed databases. </span></li></ul><h3 id=3D"efficient-parallel-com=
puting" style=3D"text-align:left"><span>Parallel Computing</span></h3><ul><=
li value=3D"1"><span>Residue Number Systems (RNS), As large integer arithme=
tic is slow due to carry propagation. CRT represent numbers as residues mod=
ulo small primes and perform&nbsp;carry-free parallel arithmetic&nbsp;(addi=
tion, multiplication).</span></li><li value=3D"2"><span>GPU Acceleration, C=
RT decomposes problems into independent sub-tasks, ideal for&nbsp;massively=
 parallel GPU computing.</span></li></ul><h3 id=3D"quantum-computing" style=
=3D"text-align:left"><span>Quantum Computing</span></h3><ul><li value=3D"1"=
><span>For Quantum Error Correction, CRT helps design&nbsp;fault-tolerant q=
uantum gates&nbsp;by decomposing operations into smaller moduli.</span></li=
><li value=3D"2"><span>In Shor=E2=80=99s Algorithm, CRT is used in the&nbsp=
;final step&nbsp;to reconstruct the prime factors of large integers.</span>=
</li></ul><h3 id=3D"algorithmic-optimizations" style=3D"text-align:left"><s=
pan>Algorithmic Optimizations</span></h3><ul><li value=3D"1"><span>For Fast=
 Fourier Transform (FFT), CRT enables&nbsp;multidimensional FFTs&nbsp;by br=
eaking signals into smaller residues.</span></li><li value=3D"2"><span>In K=
nuth=E2=80=99s Modular Multiplication, CRT speeds up&nbsp;large-integer mul=
tiplication&nbsp;in cryptographic libraries.</span></li></ul><h2 id=3D"solv=
ed-example-on-chinese-remainder-theorem" style=3D"text-align:left"><b><stro=
ng>Solved Example on Chinese Remainder Theorem</strong></b></h2><p dir=3D"l=
tr"><b><strong>Suppose a certain number leaves a remainder of 2 when divide=
d by 3, a remainder of 3 when divided by 5, and a remainder of 2 when divid=
ed by 7. Find the smallest positive integer that satisfies these conditions=
 using the Chinese Remainder Theorem.</strong></b></p><p dir=3D"ltr"><b><st=
rong>Solution:</strong></b></p><blockquote><p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"text-ali=
gn: start;"><span>Let </span><i><em class=3D"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic">x<=
/em></i><span> be the number that satisfies all the given conditions:</span=
></p><ul><li value=3D"1"><span>Remainder of 2 when divided by 3</span></li>=
<li value=3D"2"><span>Remainder of 3 when divided by 5</span></li><li value=
=3D"3"><span>Remainder of 2 when divided by 7</span></li></ul><p dir=3D"ltr=
" style=3D"text-align: start;"><span>Now, as per the Chinese Remainder Theo=
rem, since the moduli (3, 5, and 7) are pairwise coprime, a unique solution=
 modulo is lcm(3,5,7)=3D105</span></p><ul><li value=3D"1"><i><em class=3D"G=
FGEditorTheme__textItalic">x </em></i><span>=E2=89=A1 2(mod 3)</span></li><=
li value=3D"2"><i><em class=3D"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic">x </em></i><span=
>=E2=89=A1 3(mod 5)</span></li><li value=3D"3"><i><em class=3D"GFGEditorThe=
me__textItalic">x </em></i><span>=E2=89=A1 2(mod 7)</span></li></ul><p dir=
=3D"ltr" style=3D"text-align: start;"><span>The modular inverses for each m=
odulus will be:</span></p><ul><li value=3D"1"><span>For 3, the modular inve=
rse of 3 modulo 5 is 2 as 3=E2=8B=852 =E2=89=A1 1(mod 5)</span></li><li val=
ue=3D"2"><span>For 5, the modular inverse of 5 modulo 7 is 3 as 5=E2=8B=853=
 =E2=89=A1 1(mod 7)</span></li><li value=3D"3"><span>For 7, the modular inv=
erse of 7 modulo 3 is 1 as 7=E2=8B=851 =E2=89=A1 1(mod 3)</span></li></ul><=
p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"text-align: start;"><span>Now calculate for </span><=
i><em class=3D"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic">x:</em></i></p><p dir=3D"ltr"><i=
><em class=3D"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic">x </em></i><span>=E2=89=A1 (2=E2=
=8B=8535=E2=8B=852)=E2=8B=85(2=E2=8B=853) + (3=E2=8B=853=E2=8B=857=E2=8B=85=
1) + (2=E2=8B=853=E2=8B=855)=E2=8B=85(1=E2=8B=851)...(mod 105)</span></p><p=
 dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"text-align: start;"><span>On solving each term we get=
, </span></p><p dir=3D"ltr"><i><em class=3D"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic">x <=
/em></i><span>=E2=89=A1 140 + 63 + 30(mod105)</span></p><p dir=3D"ltr"><i><=
em class=3D"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic">x </em></i><span>=E2=89=A1 233(mod1=
05)</span></p><p dir=3D"ltr"><i><em class=3D"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic">x =
</em></i><span>=E2=89=A1 23(mod105)</span></p><p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"text-=
align: start;"><span>=E2=88=B4 Smallest positive integer that satisfies the=
 given conditions is </span><i><em class=3D"GFGEditorTheme__textItalic">x</=
em></i><span>=3D23.</span></p></blockquote><h2 id=3D"practice-questions" st=
yle=3D"text-align:left"><span>Practice Questions on Chinese Remainder Theor=
em</span></h2><p dir=3D"ltr" style=3D"text-align: start;"><b><strong>Questi=
on 1: </strong></b><span>Solve the system of congruences:</span></p><p dir=
